  1. Plots
#correlation plot
df_cor <- select_if(bank_data2, is.numeric) %>% cor()
corrplot(df_cor, method = "number")

#Age vs Subscription
mu <- bank_data2 %>% group_by(y) %>% summarize(grp.mean=mean(age))

ggplot (bank_data2, aes(x=age)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "blue", fill = "blue", binwidth = 5) +
  facet_grid(cols=vars(y)) + 
  ggtitle('Age Distribution by Subscription') + ylab('Count') + xlab('Age') +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0,100,5)) +
  geom_vline(data=mu, aes(xintercept=grp.mean), color="red", linetype="dashed")

#Subscription based on Number of Contact during Campaign

  geom_histogram()+

  xlim(c(min=1,max=10)) +

  1. Cleaning Data

  1. Out of Sample fit: Testing data and Training Data
train_fraction <- 0.2 # fraction of data for training purposes
set.seed(126)  # set the seed to make your partition reproductible
n_obs <- nrow(bank_data2) # number of observations in biopsy data set
train_size <- floor(train_fraction * nrow(bank_data2)) # number of observations in training set
train_indices <- sample(1:n_obs, size = train_size) #sampling training data from full dataset

train_data <- bank_data2[train_indices, ] # get training data
test_data <- bank_data2[-train_indices, ] # testing data
## Fixing Training Data imbalance
table(train_data$y)
## 
##   no  yes 
## 7967 1075
#Undersampling/Oversampling to obtain a more balanced dataset
train_data$y = as.factor(train_data$y) 
# target variable you use for SMOTE function is of INT data type. 
# SMOTE can only work with factor target variable.
train <- SMOTE(y~., data = train_data, perc.over=100)
train_data <- train

# Results of undersampling/oversampling training dataset
table(train_data$y)
## 
##   no  yes 
## 2150 2150

test1 <- SMOTE(y~., data = test_data, perc.over=100) test_data <- test1 table(test_data$y)

#
rf_model<-randomForest(y ~.,data = train_data, importance=TRUE, na.action=na.roughfix,prOximity=TRUE)
varImpPlot(rf_model)

test_result <- predict(rf_model,test_data)
error <- mean(test_result != test_data$y)
print(paste('Accuracy',1-error))
## [1] "Accuracy 0.86997152257458"
#ROC curve and area under curve for this model
pr <- prediction(as.numeric(test_result), as.numeric(test_data$y))
prf <- performance(pr, measure = "tpr", x.measure = "fpr")
plot(prf)

auc <- performance(pr, measure = "auc")
auc <- auc@y.values[[1]]
auc
## [1] 0.8189778
#confusion matrix
confusionMatrix(data = test_result,
                factor(test_data$y),
                positive = "yes")
